--- layout: post title: Building a Model For Predicting Income Level --- In this study i will try to build a model for predicting income levels of people observed with 15 features like Education, Occupation, Race, Relationship and etc. Organon Project

Organon Project

1. The Project

The data set named ?ADULT_TRAIN_DATA_TABLE? is gathered from the United States Census Bureau. It contains 17 columns including the demographic information and economic conditions of the people in the sample. Target column having value 1 indicates that the person has an annual income of more than $50K.

I will try to build a classification model which predicts if a person has an annual income of more than $50K.

The model will be built on Rstudio and a report will be created in an Rmarkdown document representing all steps throughout building the model.

The project will contain following parts:

  • Data preparation steps
  • The method used for developing the predictive model
  • Interpretation of the model outputs : selected features and model performance
  • How the model is validated

2. Data Preperation

2.1 Data Import

Before starting, the double quotes removed from the source file using notepad+.

The data import has been peformed with read_csv. RECORD_ID field is just a unique id of each observation and the PROXY field has the same information with TARGET field. So they are skipped at the time of import. Our dependent variable will be TARGET field.

ORdata <- read_csv("C:/Users/Acer-nb/Downloads/ADULT TRAIN DATA TABLE modelleme.csv",
                   col_types = cols(PROXY = col_skip(), RECORD_ID = col_skip()))

2.5 Decision to Continue with Complete Cases or All Cases

Following steps have been performed for both data sets and since the algorithms perform slightly better with complete cases(without No_Info), i decided to continue with complete cases and represented the steps here.

With complete cases there isnt a significant change in overall Accuracy and Sensitivity but xaccuracy for negative predictions(TARGET=1) is slightly better.

3. THE MODEL

3.1 Create Training, Validation and Test Sets

Following codes produce training, validation and test sets from the main data set. The percentages are 60, 20 and 20.

df <- ORdataComplete

fractionTraining   <- 0.60
fractionValidation <- 0.20
fractionTest       <- 0.20

set.seed(1234)
sampleSizeTraining   <- floor(fractionTraining   * nrow(df))
sampleSizeValidation <- floor(fractionValidation * nrow(df))
sampleSizeTest       <- floor(fractionTest       * nrow(df))

set.seed(1234)
indicesTraining    <- sort(sample(seq_len(nrow(df)), size=sampleSizeTraining))
indicesNotTraining <- setdiff(seq_len(nrow(df)), indicesTraining)
indicesValidation  <- sort(sample(indicesNotTraining, size=sampleSizeValidation))
indicesTest        <- setdiff(indicesNotTraining, indicesValidation)

dfTraining   <- df[indicesTraining, ]
dfValidation <- df[indicesValidation, ]
dfTest       <- df[indicesTest, ]

3.2 Build Models

For this project i will perform gradient-boosting, C5.0 boosting, Naive Bayes, SVM algoritms to solve the classfication problem.

In order to shorten the model built times i use parallel processing library and run 4 algorihtms as follows.

library(caret)
library('doParallel')
library(C50)
library(e1071)
cl <- makeCluster(4) #number of cores
registerDoParallel(cl)
set.seed(7)
boostFit = train(TARGET~., method = "gbm", data = dfTraining, verbose = FALSE)
set.seed(7)
c50Fit <- C5.0(TARGET~.,data=dfTraining)
set.seed(7)
NaiveFit <- naiveBayes(TARGET ~ ., data = dfTraining)
set.seed(7)
SVMFit <-svm(TARGET~., data = dfTraining)
stopCluster(cl)

Now we have 4 models on hand.

3.2.2 Model Ensemble

The following codes performs the ensemble of the models and make the prediction using this new model. But there is not significant change in the performance. Overall accuracy is sligthtly better than the standalone models.

cl <- makeCluster(4) #number of cores
registerDoParallel(cl)

predBoostFit <- predict(boostFit,dfValidation)
predC50Fit <- predict(c50Fit,dfValidation)
predNaiveFit <- predict(NaiveFit,dfValidation)
predSVMFit <- predict(SVMFit,dfValidation)

predDF <- data.frame(predBoostFit,predSVMFit,predC50Fit,predNaiveFit,TARGET=dfValidation$TARGET)
combModFit <- train(TARGET~.,method="rf",data=predDF)
predModEns <- predict(combModFit,dfValidation)
confusionMatrix (dfValidation$TARGET, predict (combModFit, dfValidation))

3.3 Build Models with CV

I want to see the results when i apply cross-validation with 10 folds and 3 repeats, a common standard configuration for comparing models. Although this data set has enough observations, sometimes this method produces better results. Another reasoun i would like to do so is in order to verify boosting algorithms perform better with this data set. It is always good idea to see the performance of algorithms with different resamples of data.

library(mlbench)
library(caret)
cl <- makeCluster(4) #number of cores
registerDoParallel(cl)
# prepare training scheme
trainControl <- trainControl(method="repeatedcv", number=10, repeats=3)
# CART
set.seed(7)
mod.cart <- train(TARGET~., data=dfTraining, method="rpart", trControl=trainControl)
# GBM
set.seed(7)
mod.gbm <- train(TARGET~., data=dfTraining, method="gbm", trControl=trainControl)

4. Model Election and Running the Elected Model on Test Set

Boosting models(C5.0 and GBM) has better overall accuracy and better specificity.

C5.0 scores are very close to gradient-boosting method but it has better negative prediction value.

I think at this time it should be a business decision which method to use. Sometimes overall accuracy is important and we select GBM for this case. But sometimes predicting the negative class is important, and we select C5.0 method for increasing the accuracy in prediction of negative class. As in this case predicting if a person has an income more than 50K is the main concern i would probably select C5.0.

As seen in the following part, our model works well on the test set. Model does not have overfitting issue which means generalization is achieved well.

5. Summary

We know that 25% of data is in class TARGET=1 roughly and 75% is in TARGET=0. Algorithms process data assuming 0 is positive class and thus we expect a sensitivity score higher than 75% percent and a specificity score higher than 25%.

We have satisfactionary results at the end. Model provided 86% overall accuracy, 89% sensitivity, 75% specificity and 66% negative prediction value.
